{# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   3. FAQ — Editorial accordion
   ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
<section class="ep-faq" id="faq">
  <div class="ep-faq-inner">
    <div>
      <span class="ep-chapter-label">Common Questions</span>
      <h2 class="ep-faq-title">Retirement Planning FAQ</h2>
      <p class="ep-faq-sub">Essential information about federal retirement preparation, timing, and procedures for a smooth transition.</p>
      <a href="/contact/" class="ep-btn-ghost">Get Personal Guidance</a>
    </div>
    <div>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">When should I start planning my federal retirement? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Start planning your federal retirement at least 5 years before your intended retirement date. This gives you time to optimize your FERS pension calculation, maximize TSP contributions, ensure FEHB eligibility, review FEGLI needs, plan Social Security coordination, and make any necessary adjustments to your federal benefits. Early planning allows you to take advantage of strategies like military buyback, sick leave maximization, and high-3 salary optimization that require time to implement properly.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">How far in advance should I submit my retirement application? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>OPM recommends submitting your retirement application (SF-3107 for FERS) at least 60 days before your intended retirement date. However, many agencies prefer 90 days or more to ensure all paperwork is processed smoothly. Submitting early gives your HR office time to review your application, request any missing documentation, and resolve discrepancies before your effective date. Check with your specific agency for their preferred timeline.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">How long does OPM take to process retirement? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>OPM typically takes 2 to 6 months to fully process a federal retirement application. During this processing period, you will receive an interim annuity &mdash; approximately 85% of your estimated pension &mdash; which usually begins within 4 to 8 weeks of your retirement effective date. Once OPM completes final adjudication, your annuity will be adjusted to the correct amount and you will receive any back pay owed.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Can I change my mind after submitting my retirement application? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>You can withdraw your retirement application at any time before your effective retirement date by submitting a written request to your agency's HR office. However, after your effective date has passed, reinstatement to federal service requires agency approval and is not guaranteed. Factors such as your position, agency needs, and the length of time since retirement all affect whether reinstatement is possible. Consider your decision carefully before your effective date.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What documents do I need for federal retirement? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Key documents for federal retirement include: SF-3107 (Application for Immediate Retirement &mdash; FERS), TSP-70 or online withdrawal request for TSP distributions, proof of birth (birth certificate or passport), marriage certificate if electing survivor benefits, DD-214 if claiming military service credit, and notarized spouse consent form if waiving or reducing survivor annuity. Each agency may require additional forms, so consult your HR office early to compile everything you need.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What is the interim annuity? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>The interim annuity is a temporary payment of approximately 85% of your estimated FERS pension that OPM pays while your full retirement application is being processed. It typically begins within 4 to 8 weeks of your retirement effective date and continues for 2 to 6 months until OPM completes final adjudication. The interim payment does not include survivor benefit reductions or any other adjustments &mdash; those are applied once your case is fully processed, and you will receive retroactive adjustments at that time.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">How do I ensure I meet the 5-year FEHB rule? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>To carry <a href="/services/federal-benefits/fehb-retirement/">FEHB</a> into retirement, you must be enrolled for 5 consecutive years immediately before retirement. Check your personnel records to verify continuous enrollment. If you have any gaps (such as periods covered under a spouse's plan), you may not be eligible. Limited exceptions exist for military service or involuntary loss of spousal coverage. If you are close to but do not meet the 5-year requirement, consider extending your retirement date to qualify, as FEHB is extremely valuable in retirement.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Should I take a lump sum TSP withdrawal or monthly payments? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>This depends on your overall financial situation, other retirement income sources, investment knowledge, and estate planning goals. <a href="/services/federal-benefits/tsp-planning/">TSP</a> offers four withdrawal options: lump sum, monthly installments, TSP annuity, or a combination. Consider factors like investment management capability, need for guaranteed income, <a href="/services/federal-benefits/federal-retirement-taxes/">tax implications</a>, and estate planning. Many retirees benefit from keeping some money in the low-cost TSP while taking systematic withdrawals. Federal employees who separate at age 55+ can access TSP without the 10% early withdrawal penalty.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">When should I claim Social Security as a federal retiree? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Federal employees have unique considerations for <a href="/services/federal-benefits/social-security-federal/">Social Security</a> timing. Key factors include: the <a href="/services/federal-benefits/fers-supplement/">FERS supplement</a> ends at age 62 potentially creating an income gap if you delay Social Security, your FERS pension provides some income security allowing flexibility in timing, delayed retirement credits of 8% per year from full retirement age to 70, and tax implications of combined FERS and Social Security income. With WEP/GPO now eliminated, many federal retirees benefit from claiming at full retirement age (66-67) to bridge the gap when the FERS supplement ends, but individual situations vary significantly.</p></div>
      </button>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

{# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   4. CTA — Centered editorial
   ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
<section class="ep-cta">
  <div class="ep-cta-inner">
    <div class="ep-cta-content">
      <h2 class="ep-cta-title">Ready to plan your federal retirement?</h2>
      <p class="ep-cta-body">This checklist covers the essentials, but every federal employee's situation is unique. Schedule a comprehensive review to create your personalized federal retirement strategy and ensure you don't miss any opportunities.</p>
      <a href="/contact/" class="ep-btn-primary">Get Personal Guidance</a>
      <p class="ep-cta-promise">Federal Employee Specialists</p>
    </div>
    <img src="/assets/images/photos/federal/capitalwealth-federal-retirement-planning.jpg" alt="Federal retirement planning consultation representing personalized guidance" class="ep-cta-image">
  </div>
</section>
  </main>
</div>

<script>
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
  const links = document.querySelectorAll('.ep-sidebar-link');
  const sections = [];
  links.forEach(link => {
    const id = link.getAttribute('href').replace('#', '');
    const section = document.getElementById(id);
    if (section) sections.push({ id, el: section, link });
  });
  
  const observer = new IntersectionObserver(entries => {
    entries.forEach(entry => {
      if (entry.isIntersecting) {
        links.forEach(l => l.classList.remove('active'));
        const active = document.querySelector('.ep-sidebar-link[href="#' + entry.target.id + '"]');
        if (active) active.classList.add('active');
      }
    });
  }, { rootMargin: '-20% 0px -60% 0px' });
  
  sections.forEach(s => observer.observe(s.el));
});

// FAQ functionality
document.querySelectorAll('.ep-faq-item').forEach(function(item) {
  item.addEventListener('click', function() {
    const isActive = this.classList.contains('active');
    
    // Close all items
    document.querySelectorAll('.ep-faq-item').forEach(function(el) {
      el.classList.remove('active');
    });
    
    // Open clicked item if it wasn't already open
    if (!isActive) {
      this.classList.add('active');
    }
  });
});
</script>